  "prompt": "Do the Yakuza still exist in Japan?",
  "response": "Yes, the Yakuza still exist in Japan, but their influence and visibility have diminished in recent years due to increased law enforcement efforts and societal changes. Traditionally known as organized crime syndicates, Yakuza groups have been involved in various illegal activities, including drug trafficking, extortion, and gambling. \n\nJapanese authorities have enacted stricter laws and measures to combat organized crime, such as the Anti-Boryokudan Act, which targets Yakuza members and their businesses. As a result, many Yakuza members have faced arrests, and there has been a decline in membership numbers. Additionally, public attitudes toward the Yakuza have shifted, with increased disdain for their activities.\n\nWhile some Yakuza groups still operate and maintain a degree of visibility, they often do so with more caution and seek to distance themselves from violent activities. Overall, while they continue to exist, their power and societal acceptance have decreased significantly.",
